y activists are one of the first to have articulated themselves in relation to the neoliberal transnational order of networked governance. While this global regulatory framework emerged to deepen market logics, Matthew C. Canfield reveals how activists are leveraging this order to make more expansive social justice claims. This nuanced, deeply engaged ethnography illustrates how food sovereignty activists are cultivating new forms of transnational governance from the ground up.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFood sovereigntyzNorthwest, Pacific. 0aFood sovereignty. 0aFood supplyxPolitical aspectszNorthwest, Pacific. 0aFood supplyxPolitical aspects. 0aSocial movementszNorthwest, Pacific. 0aSocial movements. 0aTransnationalismxPolitical aspects. 7aLAW / Civil Law.2bisacsh  aethnography.  afood systems.  aglobal governance.  ahuman rights.  alaw and society.  alegal mobilization.  anetworks.  aright to food.  atranslation.  atransnational social movements.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363131140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631311423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631311/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles